1053:The iter-048 carrier predicate $\Scheme.\IsCechAcyclicCover$ (\texttt{Cohomology/StructureSheafModuleK.lean}) lifts via its consumer $\mathtt{subsingleton\_HModule}'\_\mathtt{supr\_of\_isCechAcyclicCover}$ to a $\Subsingleton$ on $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,(\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i)$. This lives at universe $u$. The iter-053+ genus carrier $\Module.\mathtt{Finite}\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1)$, on the other hand, lives at universe $u+1$, since $\genus\,C = \mathrm{finrank}_k\,(\HModule\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1)$ (iter-011) is built on the universe-$u+1$ form $\HModule = \Ext_{u+1}\,((\mathtt{constantSheaf})\,(\ModuleCat.\mathtt{of}\,k\,k))\,F\,n$. The iter-034 universal bridge $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,T \equiv_{\Module k} \HModule\,k\,F\,n$ for terminal $T$ already crosses this gap. Iter-049 chains the two: under the cover-totality hypothesis $\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i = \top$, the iter-048 conclusion $\Subsingleton\,(\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,(\bigsqcup\mathcal U))$ rewrites to $\Subsingleton\,(\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,\top)$, which iter-034's bridge (composed with $\mathtt{Equiv.subsingleton}$) transports to $\Subsingleton\,(\HModule\,k\,F\,n)$. This is the universe-$u+1$ form of iter-048's vanishing, ready to be consumed by iter-053+.
1085:The iter-049 transport requires the comparison iso $\mathtt{compIso} : \forall n, \cechCohomology\,C\,F\,\mathcal U\,n \equiv_k \HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,(\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i)$ as an \emph{explicit} argument. This forces every call site either to receive the iso as a hypothesis or to construct it from the substantive iter-052+ comparison theorem. Iter-050 packages the iso as a $\Prop$-valued typeclass: existence is wrapped via $\mathtt{Nonempty}$, an extractor recovers it via $\Classical.\mathtt{choice}$, and an instance-driven consumer chains iter-049 with the extractor so that downstream producers (iter-053+) need only provide $[\IsCechAcyclicCover\,F\,\mathcal U]$ and $[\HasCechToHModuleIso\,F\,\mathcal U]$ instances --- the iso passes silently through typeclass synthesis. The $\mathtt{Nonempty}$ wrapper is mandatory: a $\Prop$-valued class field cannot hold the data of a $\LinearEquiv$-valued $\forall n, \ldots$ functional.
1131:The iter-049 / iter-050 instance-driven consumers cover the \emph{top-supremum} case ($\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i = \top$, landing on $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$ at universe $u+1$). The iter-053+ producer for $\IsAffineHModuleVanishing\,k\,C\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)$, however, needs the \emph{intermediate-supremum} form: for an affine open $U$ of $C$, pick a basic-open cover $\mathcal U$ with $\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i = U$ (\emph{not} $= \top$), and conclude $\Subsingleton\,(\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,i\,U)$ at universe $u$. Iter-048's explicit-argument consumer $\mathtt{subsingleton\_HModule}'\_\mathtt{supr\_of\_isCechAcyclicCover}$ already provides this (Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_prime_supr_of_isCechAcyclicCover}), but it requires the comparison iso as an explicit argument. Iter-051 fills the symmetry gap: a thin instance-driven counterpart that takes $[\HasCechToHModuleIso\,F\,\mathcal U]$ as a typeclass instance instead, so the iter-053+ producer chain consumes both $[\IsCechAcyclicCover]$ and $[\HasCechToHModuleIso]$ uniformly via instance synthesis.
1161:Iter-051 lands $\Subsingleton\,(\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,(\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i))$ on the lattice supremum. The iter-054+ producer for $\IsAffineHModuleVanishing\,k\,C\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)$ on an affine open $U$ instead needs $\Subsingleton\,(\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,U)$ on the open $U$ itself; it picks a basic-open cover $\mathcal U$ of $U$ (with $\bigsqcup\mathcal U = U$ by construction) and rewrites via the equality. Iter-052 factors this rewrite into a thin theorem (mirroring iter-049's $h\,\rhd\,\mathtt{this}$ factoring at universe $u+1$ for $\HModule$), enabling the iter-054+ producer to use cleaner instance-driven synthesis.
